You could use [`preg_match_all`][1] to extract the `id` and `count` values and then [`count`][2] and [`sum`][3] them:

    $cookie = &#39;101(2)_102(3)_103(5)&#39;;
    preg_match_all(&#39;/(?&lt;=^|_)([^(]+)\((\d+)\)(?=_|$)/&#39;, $cookie, $matches);
    $ids = $matches[1];
    $counts = $matches[2];
    echo &quot;Total IDs: &quot; . count($ids) . &quot;, total count: &quot; . array_sum($counts);

Output:

    Total IDs: 3, total count: 10

[Demo on 3v4l.org][4]

Note that you may find it more useful to have an array of counts indexed by the `id` values, for which you can use [`array_combine`][5] on the output of `preg_match_all`:

    $counts = array_combine($matches[1], $matches[2]);
    echo &quot;Total IDs: &quot; . count($counts) . &quot;, total count: &quot; . array_sum($counts). PHP_EOL;


[Demo on 3v4l.org][6]


  [1]: https://www.php.net/manual/en/function.preg-match-all.php
  [2]: https://www.php.net/manual/en/function.count.php
  [3]: https://www.php.net/manual/en/function.array-sum.php
  [4]: https://3v4l.org/5Qr0B
  [5]: https://www.php.net/manual/en/function.array-combine.php
  [6]: https://3v4l.org/qFPJr

A slightly simpler version that should work as well:

    $cookie = &#39;101(2)_102(3)_103(5)&#39;;
    preg_match_all(&#39;/\((\d+)\)/&#39;, $cookie, $matches);
    [, $counts] = $matches;
    echo &#39;Total IDs: &#39;, count($counts), &#39;, total count: &#39;, array_sum($counts);

**Demo: https://3v4l.org/PQ14O**

